coll\"><div class=\"box\"><span>Grammar Point <\/span><\/div><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unb\">whom<\/span><br\/><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"eb\">Whom<\/span> is not used very often in spoken English. <span class=\"eb\">Who<\/span> is usually used as the object pronoun, especially in questions:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">Who did you invite to the party?<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">The use of <span class=\"eb\">whom<\/span> as the pronoun after prepositions is very formal:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">To whom should I address the letter?<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">He asked me with whom I had discussed it.<\/span><\/li><\/ul> In spoken English it is much more natural to use <span class=\"eb\">who<\/span> and put the preposition at the end of the sentence:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">Who should I address the letter to?<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">He asked me who I had discussed it with.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">In defining relative clauses the object pronoun <span class=\"eb\">whom<\/span> is not often used. You can either use <span class=\"eb\">who<\/span> or <span class=\"eb\">that<\/span>, or leave out the pronoun completely:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">The family (who\/that\/whom) I met at the airport were very kind.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">In non-defining relative clauses <span class=\"eb\">who<\/span> or, more formally, <span class=\"eb\">whom<\/span> (but not <span class=\"ei\">that<\/span>) is used and the pronoun cannot be left out:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">Our doctor, who\/whom we all liked very much, retired last week.<\/span><\/li><\/ul> This pattern is not used very much in spoken English.<\/li><\/ul><\/span><\/div> <\/li><\/div>","meanDetailEng":"used instead of \u2018who\u2019 as the object of a verb or preposition","antonym":"whom,whomever,whomsoever","exampleEng1":"Whom did they invite?","exam